B.afQ=new A.c("Diagram 2-1 shows where White, in an attempt to cope with Black's bo-gin (climbing Silver), has just dropped a Bishop on 5d. If P2d, Px2d, Sx2d as Black intends to play, White can then drop a Pawn on 2g blocking the Rook's path.")
B.akx=new A.c("So, the move Black should play in Diagram 2-1 is...?")
B.a09=A.a(s(["B*3h"]),t.s)
B.aa7=new A.O(null,B.a09,B.l)
B.amN=new A.c("B*3h in response to B*5d. This was first played by Kozo Masuda in 1955, and now is the move you should know (joseki) when playing bo-gin.")
B.UL=A.a(s(["B*3h","P-1d","P-2d","Px2d","Sx2d","P*2g"]),t.s)
B.a9o=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 2-1:",B.UL,B.l)
B.amO=new A.c("You don't have to worry about your Silver being repelled by White's P1d. You can keep your offense along the second file. What if White plays P*2g? Calm down, this is where you have to keep your cool.")
B.WC=A.a(s(["Bx2g","Sx2d","Bx5d","Px5d","Rx2d"]),t.s)
B.a9k=new A.O("Moves thereafter:",B.WC,B.l)
B.NE=new A.p("ln1gk2nl/1r4g2/p1sp1p3/2p1p1pRp/1p7/2P6/PPSPPPP1P/2G6/LN2KG1NL w BS2Pbs","Diagram 2-2")
B.an7=new A.c("After your Bx2g White will take your Silver on 2d, apparently for free, but you can take White's Silver back by playing Bx5d and Rx2d.")
B.aie=new A.c('Look at Diagram 2-2. White has no Pawn in hand, which means it will not be easy for White to defend the second file. Having "Bishop for Bishop" well applied, Black has a very good position here.')
B.VT=A.a(s([B.ais,B.Mc,B.afQ,B.akx,B.aa7,B.amN,B.a9o,B.amO,B.a9k,B.NE,B.an7,B.aie]),t.A)
B.acN=new A.aq(B.VT)
B.a2G=A.a(s([B.adc,B.acN]),t.l)
B.aoX=new A.bg(13,B.aN,"Oppose Bishop with Bishop","Kaku niwa Kaku",B.a2G)
B.agG=new A.c("The Horse can be surprisingly difficult to use in offense. It should be far more effective if the Horse is placed in your own camp threatening the opponent's camp from afar. This is the idea behind the proverb.")
B.Lq=new A.p("ln1g4+B/1ks1g4/1p2s4/p1ppp1p1p/9/P1P1P1P1P/1P1P5/2KSG4/LN1GS2rL b RNL3Pbnp","Diagram 1-1")
B.ank=new A.c("Diagram 1-1 shows where White has just dropped a Rook on 2i. If Black plays likewise: R*4a, White will then play P*2b blocking the path of Black's Horse.")
B.Nu=new A.p("ln1g1R2+B/1ks1g2p1/1p2s4/p1ppp1p1p/9/P1P1P1P1P/1P1P5/2KSG4/LN1GS2rL b NL3Pbn","Diagram 1-2")
B.akA=new A.c("If the Dragon instead of the Horse was in White's camp as in Diagram 1-3, Black can play +R2i after P*2b. In this way Black can place the Dragon on a vital point in just one move. But in Diagram 1-2, Black has to play two moves, i.e.,+B1b and +Bx3d, before the Horse comes to a good square.")
B.aja=new A.c("You should always be prepared for the opponent's blocking Pawn drop.")
B.PD=new A.p("ln1g5/1ks1g2p+R/1p2s4/p1ppp1p1p/9/P1P1P1P1P/1P1P5/2KSG4/LN1GS2rL b BNL3Pbn","Diagram 1-3")
B.afb=new A.c("Back in Diagram 1-1, the move you should play is +B6f (Diagram 1-4). See for yourself that the Horse is on a very good square both in offense and defense.")
B.OF=new A.p("ln1g5/1ks1g4/1p2s4/p1ppp1p1p/9/P1P+BP1P1P/1P1P5/2KSG4/LN1GS2rL w RNL3Pbnp","Diagram 1-4")
B.ZY=A.a(s(["Rx1i+","P9e","Px9e","P*9c"]),t.s)
B.a9h=new A.O("Moves after Diagram 1-4:",B.ZY,B.u)
B.Pn=new A.p("ln1g5/1ks1g4/Pp2s4/2ppp1p1p/p8/2P+BP1P1P/1P1P5/2KSG4/LN1GS3+r w RNL2Pbnl2p","Diagram 1-5")
B.akF=new A.c("With the Horse behind, the edge attack is quite effective.")
B.aly=new A.c("After Diagram 1-5, if White plays Lx9c, you can go on to play P*9d. White will respond with Lx9d, then you can play N*8f, claiming a Lance on 9d and a Pawn on 7d at the same time. This is a quite favorable position for you.")
B.ahV=new A.c("Remember this all results from the Horse being pulled back in your own camp.")
