B.Wm=A.a(s([B.ad8,B.ae8,B.adL]),t.l)
B.app=new A.bg(20,B.bD,"Defend the King with three Generals, Attack with Rook, Bishop, Silver and Knight","Gyoku no mamori wa Kin Gin 3 mai, seme wa Hi, Kaku, Gin, Kei",B.Wm)
B.aex=new A.c("So long as you see the castle as a space secured for your King, you should push the edge Pawn thereby making more room for the King to breathe. However, if the opponent has also built up the Yagura castle, the opponent's attacking pieces will therefore be at your King's head. You may invite a premature clash by advancing the edge Pawn. So, do be careful. This is what the proverb teaches.")
B.Ns=new A.p("ln5nl/1r1s1bgk1/3p1gspp/ppp1ppp2/9/2PPP1PP1/PPSG1PN1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 1-1")
B.aj1=new A.c("If you play P9f in Diagram 1-1, there will follow:")
B.Yz=A.a(s(["P9f","P8e","P4f","S7c"]),t.s)
B.a8T=new A.O(null,B.Yz,B.l)
B.N6=new A.p("ln5nl/1r3bgk1/2sp1gspp/p1p1ppp2/1p7/P1PPPPPP1/1PSG2N1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 1-2")
B.amr=new A.c("If you push up your edge Pawn in the same file as your opponent did his, you may let a fight start on the left wing. When you play White, S7c is a move to play after Black has played P9f.")
B.Zd=A.a(s(["S4g","S8d","P2e"]),t.s)
B.aa1=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 1-2:",B.Zd,B.l)
B.aeM=new A.c("Both sides have paved their way to begin an attack, but you should note that White is a step ahead because of Black's P9f.")
B.Vw=A.a(s(["P9e","Px9e","Sx9e","Lx9e","Lx9e"]),t.s)
B.a9x=new A.O("Then there will follow:",B.Vw,B.u)
B.Mh=new A.p("1n5nl/1r3bgk1/3p1gspp/2p1ppp2/lp5P1/2PPPPP2/1PSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/1N6L b SPlp","Diagram 1-3")
B.afv=new A.c("See the price Black has to pay just because he hasn't observed the proverb. White's Sx9e is what you should remember when attacking the edge file with the Bo-gin.")
B.anW=new A.c("From Diagram 1-3, White can play R9b or P*9g, while Black is far from being comfortable having a skirmish started quite close to his King.")
B.To=A.a(s([B.aex,B.Ns,B.aj1,B.a8T,B.N6,B.amr,B.aa1,B.aeM,B.a9x,B.Mh,B.afv,B.anW]),t.A)
B.adZ=new A.aq(B.To)
B.ahk=new A.c("What if you don't play P9f in Diagram 1-1?")
B.SQ=A.a(s(["P4f","P9e","S4g","N7c","P2e"]),t.s)
B.aaZ=new A.O(null,B.SQ,B.l)
B.PG=new A.p("l6nl/1r1s1bgk1/2np1gspp/1pp1ppp2/p6P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L w -","Diagram 2-1")
B.ahP=new A.c("By not playing P9f in response to P9d, you have managed to keep White's attacking pieces at bay. You have allowed him to advance his edge Pawn to 9e instead, but Diagram 1-2 shows that you are the one to go first.")
B.akw=new A.c("Again back in Diagram 1-1, what if White resorts to the Bo-gin?")
B.a2g=A.a(s(["P4f","P8e","S4g","S7c","P2e","S8d"]),t.s)
B.aa2=new A.O(null,B.a2g,B.l)
B.Oj=new A.p("ln5nl/1r3bgk1/3p1gspp/psp1ppp2/1p5P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-2")
B.akM=new A.c("You have nothing to worry about. When White plays S9e, you can chase it away by P9f. Also in this position, you are the one to take the initiative.")
B.akj=new A.c("Lastly, let me add the position in which you can play the edge Pawn. If White's Knight is on 7c at an early stage, as in Diagram 2-3, you can safely play P9f. In other words, as long as it's certain that White does not employ the Bo-gin, you can play P9f after White's P9d.")
B.N4=new A.p("l6nl/1r1s1bgk1/2np1gspp/ppp1ppp2/9/2PPP1PP1/PPSG1PN1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-3")
B.amW=new A.c("This is my personal opinion, but when you play the double fortress opening, it is better to play something for the future offense rather than playing the defensive move (P9f in response to P9d).")
B.a3v=A.a(s([B.ahk,B.aaZ,B.PG,B.ahP,B.akw,B.aa2,B.Oj,B.akM,B.akj,B.N4,B.amW]),t.A)
B.ad2=new A.aq(B.a3v)
B.a_V=A.a(s([B.adZ,B.ad2]),t.l)
B.aoY=new A.bg(21,B.bD,"In the Yagura Opening, Don't Push the Edge Pawn","Yagura-gakoi ni hashi-fu wo tsukuna",B.a_V)
B.ajh=new A.c("The edge Pawn in the Mino-castle could play a crucial role. When your opponent plays P1d as in Diagram 1, you'd best respond with P1f. Later on the square of 1g will mean a great deal for your King.")
B.OM=new A.p("8l/9/7p1/6p1p/9/9/5PPPP/4G1SK1/5G1NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.ah8=new A.c("Had your opponent's Pawn come to 9e, as in Diagram 2, and if your Gold on 6a were taken, your King will be mated in three moves: S*7a, K-9b, G*8b.")
B.Mk=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/ppp6/9/P8/2P6/1P7/9/L8 b GS","Diagram 2")
B.am0=new A.c("In Diagram 3, however, Black will need four Generals to mate the King.")
B.NQ=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/1pp6/p8/9/P1P6/1P7/9/L8 b 2G2S","Diagram 3")
B.a06=A.a(s(["S*7a","K9b","G*9c","Kx9c","S*8b","K9b","Sx9a+","K9c","S8b-","Kx8b","G*9b"]),t.s)
B.a91=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 3:",B.a06,B.l)
B.anH=new A.c("You should not drop a Gold on 9b as in Diagram 2. The King will then sit on 9c, and you won't be able to check any further.")
B.ajQ=new A.c("Compare those two diagrams above and see what a difference an edge Pawn can make when the King is in the Mino-castle. The edge square secured by pushing up a Pawn was worth two Generals in this case.")
B.NC=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/1pp6/9/p8/2P6/PP7/9/L8 b 3G3S","Diagram 4")
B.ai8=new A.c("What if the edge Pawn was another square ahead (Diagram 4)? In order to mate White's King, you will need as many as six Generals.")
B.ZL=A.a(s(["S*7a","K-9b","G*9c","Kx9c","S*8b","K-9d","S*8e","Kx8e","G*7e","K-9d","G*8e"]),t.s)
B.a8M=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 4:",B.ZL,B.l)
B.ai9=new A.c("If, after the 5th move in the above, White plays K9b, it will be even quicker: G*9c, Nx9c, Sx9a+, Kx9a, G*8b.")
B.anK=new A.c("Now I hope I have made it clear that pushing up the edge Pawn, which is a part of the Mino-castle, can earn a lot: each square gained means two Generals.")
B.alD=new A.c("When you build up the Mino-castle, don't forget to push up the edge Pawn. You won't regret it, especially toward the endgame.")
B.a3O=A.a(s([B.ajh,B.OM,B.ah8,B.Mk,B.am0,B.NQ,B.a91,B.anH,B.ajQ,B.NC,B.ai8,B.a8M,B.ai9,B.anK,B.alD]),t.A)
B.ad7=new A.aq(B.a3O)
B.a27=A.a(s([B.ad7]),t.l)
B.apy=new A.bg(22,B.bD,"Push up the Edge Pawn When Playing the Mino Castle","Mino-gakoi wa hashifu wo tsuke",B.a27)
B.amK=new A.c("Before you begin to build up your castle, be sure to look at your opponent's camp as well as yours. Pay attention, above all, where the opponent's Bishop sits. Placing your King on the Bishop's diagonal can be very dangerous.")
B.Nc=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p1n1pp1pp/1ppps1p2/9/2PPP4/PPSG1PPPP/1KGB1S1R1/LN5NL w -","Diagram 1")
B.anE=new A.c("Diagram 1 shows where Black has played K-8h, in the Yagura castle: a normal move, apparently. But it turned out to be a bad move, since the King moved into a dangerous zone.")
B.Y2=A.a(s(["N8e","S8f","P6e"]),t.s)
B.a9I=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 1:",B.Y2,B.u)
B.Op=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p3pp1pp/1pp1s1p2/1n1p5/1SPPP4/PP1G1PPPP/1KGB1S1R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 2")
B.afn=new A.c("N8e is a smart move on White's part. Naturally Black avoids offering his Silver in exchange for a Knight; therefore, he plays S8f, but White's next move, P6e, gives Black a headache. Black cannot play Px6e.")
B.Zf=A.a(s(["S5g","Px6f","Sx6f","S6e"]),t.s)
B.aax=new A.O("Moves thereafter:",B.Zf,B.l)
B.Lv=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p3pp1pp/1pp3p2/1n1s5/1SPSP4/PP1G1PPPP/1KGB3R1/LN5NL b Pp","Diagram 3")
B.akk=new A.c("In Diagram 3, Black is already in a losing position.")
B.aiv=new A.c("Back in Diagram 1 where White is ready to attack from the 6th file, Black should have built a different type of castle, like the one in Diagram 4 (last move N7c). You don't have to stick to the authentic Yagura castle at all times. Even if you cannot complete the castle and leave it as in Diagram 4, it does not mean that you are in a bad position.")
B.LS=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sg2/p1n1ppbpp/1ppps1p2/7P1/2PPP1P2/PP1GSP2P/1BGS3R1/LNK4NL b -","Diagram 4")
B.ah6=new A.c("As a guideline, you should remember, unless there are two pieces or more that are interposed between the Bishop and your King, it won't be safe to place your King in the Bishop's diagonal. You should note, however, in case those interposed pieces are sure to be attacked, for instance by White's N8e and P6e as in Diagram 1, it is not at all safe. Don't forget that the Bishop's diagonal can be quite dangerous for your King.")
B.Vj=A.a(s([B.amK,B.Nc,B.anE,B.a9I,B.Op,B.afn,B.aax,B.Lv,B.akk,B.aiv,B.LS,B.ah6]),t.A)
B.adD=new A.aq(B.Vj)
B.a2k=A.a(s([B.adD]),t.l)
B.aph=new A.bg(23,B.bD,"Don't Put the King on the Bishop's Diagonal","Gyoku wa Kaku-suji wo sakeyo",B.a2k)
B.aeG=new A.c("Depending on which Pawns are pushed in the opening, the future strategy varies. Diagram 1 (last move P6d) shows where Black has aligned his Pawns in the fourth row along the 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th and 9th file, quite observant of the proverb in question. As a matter of fact, this formation will work best in a quick attack scheme with the Rook in its original position.")
B.MB=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbp1/p2p1pp1p/7P1/P1P1P1P1P/1P1PSP3/1BKGGS1R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.akl=new A.c("For the sake of argument, see the position below where Pawns in the even number files are all a square ahead. You can see how problematic it is for the Bishop to be effective. This explains the idea behind the proverb.")
B.OA=new A.p("9/9/9/9/9/1P1P1P1P1/P1P1P1P1P/1B7/9 b -","Diagram 2")
B.amS=new A.c("When the game becomes slow, you are likely to push up other Pawns as well, like Diagram 3 (last move B2f). But remember, odd number first, then even number. This is the general idea.")
B.Pj=new A.p("ln3r1nl/1kg6/1s1g1sbp1/ppppppp1p/7P1/PPPPPPPBP/1S1GS4/1KG4R1/LN5NL w -","Diagram 3")
B.alE=new A.c("Also in the Yagura opening, you first play with the odd-number file Pawns. See Diagram 4 (last move P7d) how both Bishops are threatening each other camp with the 3rd, 5th and 7th file Pawns neatly positioned for their Bishops to pass.")
B.OR=new A.p("ln3kbnl/1r1sg1g2/p2p2spp/1pp1ppp2/9/2PPP1P2/PPSG1P1PP/2G2S1R1/LNBK3NL b -","Diagram 4")
B.aio=new A.c("Needless to say, the proverb is not against the advancement of the Pawns in the even-number files at all times.")
B.Ur=A.a(s([B.aeG,B.MB,B.akl,B.OA,B.amS,B.Pj,B.alE,B.OR,B.aio]),t.A)
B.adA=new A.aq(B.Ur)
B.UY=A.a(s([B.adA]),t.l)
B.aoU=new A.bg(24,B.bD,"In the Opening Push up Pawns in the Odd-number Files","Joban wa kisuu no Fu wo tsuke",B.UY)
B.ahN=new A.c("Suppose your Pawn is on the f-rank directly opposite your opponent's Pawn on the d-rank, then the threat is even. Neither side has a kurai. But if yours is on the e-rank preventing the opponent's Pawn to advance further, you have a kurai in that file. Taking a kurai means to restrict the opponent's moves. But sometimes it can be a target at which your opponent makes an attack.")
B.ai_=new A.c("The proverb above teaches that you should not only hold the vanguard Pawn steady, but make sure it won't be a target from your opponent.")
B.Ne=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbpp/p2p1pp2/4P2P1/P1P1SPP2/1P1P4P/1BKSG2R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-1")
B.af7=new A.c("Diagram 1-1 shows where Black has just played to support the Pawn on 5e (called the 5e-kurai-dori) against White's ranging Rook opening.")
B.aks=new A.c("Diagram 1-2 is called gyoku-to-kurai-dori (King's head kurai-dori), where Black has played S7f to the same effect.")
B.On=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbpp/p2p1pp2/2P1P2P1/P1S6/1P1PSPP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-2")
B.alm=new A.c("Please note that in both cases a Silver goes up to support the Pawn on e. The Silver is the most suitable reinforcing piece on the front.")
B.amU=new A.c("Look again at both Diagrams. See that even if White tries a counterattack against the vanguard Pawn, Black can summon another Silver to the front in just one move.")
B.aky=new A.c("One more thing about a kurai. Look at Diagram 1-3.")
B.NA=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2P1P4/2SPS2P1/PP3PP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL b -","Diagram 1-3")
B.ajR=new A.c("Black has two kurai's here, but that's simply too good to get away with. You will end up incurring heaps of troubles trying to keep those two footholds, unless you have the position like one below (Diagram 1-4), where the kurai's are side by side, on top of two Silvers placed close-by. That's only when your two kurai's work.")
B.Mo=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2PP5/2SSP2P1/PP3PP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL b -","Diagram 1-4")
B.SE=A.a(s([B.ahN,B.ai_,B.Ne,B.af7,B.aks,B.On,B.alm,B.amU,B.aky,B.NA,B.ajR,B.Mo]),t.A)
B.ady=new A.aq(B.SE)
B.afD=new A.c("A vanguard Pawn is a pretty good thing to have, from which you can build up your future strategy, but it could work against you at times.")
B.Pm=new A.p("lnsgkg1nl/1r5b1/ppppps1pp/5pp2/4P4/2P3PP1/PP1P1P2P/1B3S1R1/LNSGKG1NL w -","Diagram 2-1")
B.ajN=new A.c("In Diagram 2-1, Black has just played to make the midfile-Pawn into a vanguard (P5e), but it was a bad idea.")
B.UA=A.a(s(["R5b","S5g","P5d","Px5d","Sx5d"]),t.s)
B.aaf=new A.O("After Diagram 2-1:",B.UA,B.u)
B.Nd=new A.p("lnsgkg1nl/4r2b1/pppp3pp/4spp2/9/2P3PP1/PP1PSP2P/1B5R1/LNSGKG1NL b Pp","Diagram 2-2")
B.akB=new A.c("Above is a typical example where White's counterattack worked. Black should have known his S5g was too late to support the Pawn on 5e.")
B.alM=new A.c("Diagram 2-3 (last move P8e) is another illustration of an attempted vanguard Pawn from a Yagura opening.")
B.MG=new A.p("ln4knl/1r1s2g2/p2p1gspp/2pbppp2/1p7/2PPP1P2/PPSG1PSPP/1KGB3R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 2-3")
B.Yv=A.a(s(["P6e","B4b","S6f","P8f"]),t.s)
B.aaj=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 2-3 (1):",B.Yv,B.l)
B.aew=new A.c("It is never easy to create a vanguard Pawn in the double fortress opening. In Diagram 2-3, it may appear quite easy for Black to take a kurai in the 6th file by playing P6e. But White will then play P8f to exchange Pawns, which is hardly desirable for Black. What if, then, you play G6f instead of S6f so that White cannot come for the Pawn-exchange in the 8th file?")
B.UU=A.a(s(["P6e","B4b","G6f","S7c","P2f","R6b"]),t.s)
B.ab2=new A.O("Moves from Diagram 2-3 (2):",B.UU,B.l)
B.Mu=new A.p("ln4knl/3r1bg2/p1sp1gspp/2p1ppp2/1p1P5/2PGP1PP1/PPS2PS1P/1KGB3R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 2-4")
B.ak9=new A.c("White will then shift the Rook on the 6th file, so that he can play P6d, Px6d, Sx6d.")
B.ajn=new A.c("Remember, you had better not try to keep the vanguard Pawn at the cost of breaking a part of the castle. Especially when playing the Yagura, don't think of having a vanguard Pawn unless your left Silver can go up to support the Pawn.")
B.X8=A.a(s([B.afD,B.Pm,B.ajN,B.aaf,B.Nd,B.akB,B.alM,B.MG,B.aaj,B.aew,B.ab2,B.Mu,B.ak9,B.ajn]),t.A)
B.adG=new A.aq(B.X8)
B.UT=A.a(s([B.ady,B.adG]),t.l)
B.apg=new A.bg(25,B.bD,"Make a Vanguard Pawn, then Make it Stick","Kurai wo tottara kurai no kakuho",B.UT)
B.agm=new A.c("People used to take this proverb quite seriously, and did the best they could to prevent the opponent from maintaining a 5e vanguard Pawn. But in present-day shogi, it does not always hold true.")
B.aeZ=new A.c("Diagram 1 (last move K4a) shows where White has successfully realized the 5e vanguard Pawn. The position is supposed to be in favor of White according to the proverb, but not so in reality.")
B.MQ=new A.p("ln1g1k1nl/4r1gb1/p1pp1s1p1/4spp1p/4p4/P1P2PPRP/1P1PPSN2/1BKGSG3/LN6L b Pp","Diagram 1")
B.aj8=new A.c("See how Black's R,B,S,and N are ideally placed for an attack.")
B.T0=A.a(s(["P3e","Px3e","P4e","Px4e","P5f","Px5f"]),t.s)
B.ab_=new A.O(null,B.T0,B.l)
B.anB=new A.c("First he plays P3e before moving the Knight, and then P5f, thereby aiming at the Pawn on 5e. These are orthodox and effective moves on Black's part.")
B.Vg=A.a(s(["Bx2b+","Gx2b","Sx5f"]),t.s)
B.a8Z=new A.O("Then there will follow:",B.Vg,B.l)
B.NF=new A.p("ln1g1k1nl/4r2g1/p1pp1s1p1/4s3p/5pp2/P1P1S2RP/1P1P2N2/2KGSG3/LN6L w B2Pb4p","Diagram 2")
B.agH=new A.c("If White plays P*5e to keep the vanguard, Black can play S4e asking for Silver-exchange so that his Knight can leap onto 4e.")
